messages.content: You are tasked with creating a structured output from the provided user message.

Full HTTP request path
- /invoices/{id}

Why:
- The invoices router is mounted at /invoices in index.js (app.use('/invoices', invoiceRoutes)).
- In routes/invoices.js, the endpoint for retrieving a single invoice is defined as router.get('/:id', getInvoice).
- Therefore, the full path for getInvoice is /invoices/:id, and per the requirement, path parameters are shown as {id} -> /invoices/{id}.

HTTP methods analysis (based on code)

- All HTTP methods acceptable: No
  - The endpoint is only implemented for GET (and also supports other methods like PATCH/DELETE on the same path in the router, but those are distinct handlers). There is no universal acceptance of all methods for this single path.

- HEAD acceptable: Yes
  - Express automatically supports HEAD requests for routes defined with GET. Since getInvoice is a GET route, HEAD requests to /invoices/{id} will be handled by Express without an explicit handler.

- POST acceptable: No
  - There is no POST route defined for /invoices/{id}. The POST route exists for /invoices (createInvoice) but not for a specific /invoices/{id} path.

- OPTIONS acceptable: Yes
  - The app uses the CORS middleware (app.use(cors())). CORS handles preflight OPTIONS requests, so OPTIONS requests to this path are handled by the middleware.

- TRACE acceptable: No
  - There is no TRACE handler anywhere in the code, and Express does not provide TRACE for this path by default.

- GET acceptable: Yes
  - The endpoint is explicitly defined as router.get('/:id', getInvoice).

- PUT acceptable: No
  - There is no PUT route defined for /invoices/{id}. The code uses PATCH (and DELETE) for that path.

- DELETE acceptable: Yes
  - The router defines router.delete('/:id', deleteInvoice), so DELETE /invoices/{id} is supported.

- PATCH acceptable: Yes
  - The router defines router.patch('/:id', updateInvoice), so PATCH /invoices/{id} is supported.

Explanation
- The endpoint that processes getInvoice is wired through the invoices router under the /invoices base path. The getInvoice function handles GET requests to /invoices/{id} and returns the invoice by ID.
- HEAD is considered acceptable because Express provides automatic HEAD support for GET routes.
- OPTIONS is acceptable due to the Cors middleware handling preflight requests.
- Other HTTP methods (POST, PUT) are not applicable to /invoices/{id} based on the explicit routes defined; PATCH and DELETE are defined and therefore acceptable for this path.
- TRACE is not implemented anywhere, so it is not acceptable.
